## 0. Preface & Complete Overall Implementation Idea (Required Core Logic)
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The full physical and molecular implementation path of the ELEANOR platform is based on **nasal minimally invasive implantation of flexible soft electrodes**, which is used as the physical access port of the entire system. The soft electrode is connected with a large number of conductive DNA strands modified with polythiophene and pyrene groups, and these conductive DNA molecules enter the neuronal cytoplasm through cell-penetrating peptides (CPP). Through specific coupling (SpyTag/SpyCatcher covalent self-locking) and non-specific binding (π-π stacking, electrostatic adsorption), the conductive DNA is stably connected with intracellular conductive proteins or pathological conductive aggregates to form a complete, closed, low-loss extracellular-intracellular electrical circuit. On the basis of this stable conductive circuit, the platform splits into two parallel functional routes: one uses the circuit to target Alzheimer’s disease lesions and induce local autophagy to clear amyloid deposits for clinical treatment; the other uses the circuit to achieve high-resolution single-cell neural signal reading through cytoplasmic DNA barcoding, scaffold protein potential sensing, and machine learning decoding, forming a next-generation ethically compliant brain-computer interface system. The entire system operates completely in the neuronal cytoplasm, without nuclear entry, without genomic editing, without any signal writing behavior, and meets all biosafety and ethical standards.
