## 1. Overall Core Design Concept (Full Architecture Overview)
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The ELEANOR platform is an original, cytoplasm-restricted dual-module neural engineering system that is completely oriented to real clinical demands and long-term neural technology evolution. This platform is divided into two fully independent, non-interfering, parallel technical routes without any functional crosstalk, aiming to solve two major global problems: the lack of effective targeted treatment for Alzheimer’s disease (AD), and the lack of high-resolution, ethically compliant, long-term stable brain-computer interface (BCI) technology.
The entire system abides by three non-negotiable bottom lines: all molecular operations are limited to the neuronal cytoplasm, no nuclear entry and no genomic editing; the BCI route only achieves neural signal reading, completely abandoning signal writing to comply with global neuroethical norms; all materials and technical parameters are within the scope of biosafety and clinical translation standards.
The two core routes are defined as follows:
1. Clinical Priority Route (Disease Treatment First): Targeted therapy for AD based on SpyTag/SpyCatcher covalent self-locking bridging technology, polythiophene-pyrene dual-modified conductive DNA, π-π stacking conductive pathway, and weak electrically induced autophagy. This route uses only mature, peer-reviewed, experimentally verified technologies, with a clear preclinical and clinical translation path, and can complete mouse model verification within 18-24 months.
2. Technological Inevitability Route (Scientific Trend First): Single-cell resolution read-only BCI system based on engineered Drt3b-mediated cytoplasmic poly(AC) synthesis, NES-Cas9 edited DNA barcoding, AAV-delivered NF-L（Neurofilament light chain） cytoplasmic scaffold, and flexible graphene soft electrode coupling. This route represents the next generation of non-invasive, high spatial resolution neural interface technology, and advances steadily with the optimization of frontier enzymes and materials.
The two routes share a set of unified underlying core technologies, including chemically stabilized anti-hydrolysis DNA, CPP-mediated non-invasive blood-brain barrier crossing delivery, NES-Cas9 cytoplasmic anchoring system, multi-layer composite coating for conductivity and stability enhancement, and SpyTag/SpyCatcher covalent self-locking system. All technical details are supported by peer-reviewed literature, and all potential risks and doubts are addressed with detailed engineering solutions and scientific evidence.
