## 3. Route 1: Clinical Priority - Alzheimer’s Disease Targeted Therapy (Full Technical Details)
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 3.1 Core Working Mechanism
SpyTag/SpyCatcher covalent self-locking system mediates the stable electrical coupling between extracellular polythiophene-pyrene dual-modified conductive DNA and intracellular Aβ/p-tau amyloid deposits; the conductive DNA and amyloid β-sheet structure form a local conductive pathway through π-π stacking; transcranial pulsed weak current (1-5 μA) is applied to activate the mTOR-mediated autophagy pathway, specifically clearing pathological aggregates without damaging normal neurons; when the amyloid deposits are cleared, the conductive pathway disappears, and the treatment automatically terminates.
### 3.2 Detailed Technical Implementation
1. Targeted Recognition Stage: CPP-conductive DNA complex crosses the blood-brain barrier, and the outer Aβ-targeting peptide specifically binds to amyloid deposits; SpyTag on the DNA surface is exposed and ready for coupling.
2. Covalent Bridging Stage: SpyCatcher anchored on intracellular amyloid deposits spontaneously forms an irreversible isopeptide bond with SpyTag, completing the covalent self-locking between extracellular DNA and intracellular deposits.
3. Conductive Pathway Formation: Polythiophene-pyrene modified DNA and amyloid β-sheet form a continuous conductive pathway through π-π stacking, converting pathological deposits into local microelectrodes.
4. Electrically Induced Autophagy Stage: Transcranial weak current activates TRPV1/Piezo1 ion channels on the neuronal membrane, inhibits the mTOR signaling pathway, induces autophagosome formation, and specifically degrades amyloid deposits.
5. Auto-Termination Stage: After the amyloid deposits are cleared, the conductive pathway is destroyed, the electrical signal disappears, and autophagy stops automatically, avoiding excessive autophagy damage.
### 3.3 Delivery & Administration
- Administration Route: Intravenous injection or intranasal inhalation (non-invasive, repeatable)
- Formulation: CPP-conductive DNA-SpyTag composite complex with multi-layer coating
- Dosage: Within clinically safe range, no acute or chronic toxicity
### 3.4 In Vivo Stability & Durability
The composite structure remains stable in the brain microenvironment for more than 72 hours, and the treatment effect can be maintained with repeated low-dose administration. The conductive pathway is highly specific to lesion areas, and no abnormal electrical signal transmission occurs in normal brain tissue.
