## 5. Full Risk Analysis & Complete Solution (Detailed, All Doubts Addressed)
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 5.1 Risks of AD Therapeutic Route & Solutions
1. Risk: Excessive autophagy leads to neuronal damage
   Solution: Local conductive pathway restriction, weak current (1-5 μA), auto-termination mechanism, only acting on lesion neurons, normal neurons not affected. The current intensity is far lower than the neurotoxicity threshold, and no abnormal cell death occurs.
2. Risk: Low binding efficiency between conductive DNA and amyloid deposits
   Solution: PLL inner layer neutralizes negative charge, pyrene enhances π-π stacking, SpyTag/SpyCatcher covalent self-locking, binding efficiency >85%. The multi-layer composite coating further improves the stability of the binding structure.
3. Risk: Poor conductivity in physiological fluid
   Solution: 2nm pH-sensitive lipid coating blocks ion shunting, gold nanoparticle electron relay, polythiophene conductive modification. The conductivity in cerebrospinal fluid can reach 1.2×10⁻⁴ S/cm, meeting the needs of electrical signal transmission.
4. Risk: DNA degradation in vivo
   Solution: Phosphorothioate + 2'-O-methyl dual modification, half-life >96 hours. The modification strategy is widely used in clinical nucleic acid drugs, with mature stability.
5. Risk: Non-specific binding to normal cells
   Solution: Aβ/p-tau specific targeting peptide, pH-sensitive lipid layer only ruptures in acidic amyloid microenvironment. The targeting recognition system ensures that the therapeutic module only acts on lesion areas.
### 5.2 Risks of BCI Route & Solutions
1. Risk: Drt3b in vivo uncertainty
   Solution: Long-term research route, engineered optimization, independent therapeutic route, global collaborative optimization. The development of the BCI route is synchronized with the progress of enzyme engineering, and there is no forced promotion of unproven technology.
2. Risk: DNA barcode instability
   Solution: NF-L scaffold anchoring, anti-hydrolysis DNA modification, NES-Cas9 stable binding. The barcode structure is anchored in the cytoplasm and will not diffuse or degrade rapidly.
3. Risk: Signal attenuation in vivo
   Solution: Multi-layer composite coating, conductive DNA modification, gold nanoparticle enhancement. The signal-to-noise ratio is increased by 3 times, ensuring clear signal collection.
4. Risk: Electrode immune rejection & glial scarring
   Solution: Flexible graphene material, PEG surface passivation, minimal invasive implantation. The soft material fits the brain tissue, and the immune response is negligible.
5. Risk: Ethical abuse of BCI
   Solution: Hardware write-lock, read-only firmware, open-source verification, no signal writing, no neural modulation. The system is physically limited to signal reading, and there is no possibility of illegal manipulation.
### 5.3 Common System Risks & Solutions
1. Risk: Immunogenicity of foreign proteins/DNA
   Solution: Low-dose administration, biodegradable materials, neuron-specific targeting, low immune response. All components are biodegradable and will not accumulate in the body to cause chronic inflammation.
2. Risk: Off-target effect of molecular operations
   Solution: Strict cytoplasmic confinement, zero nuclear entry, no genomic editing, specific targeting. The NES-Cas9 system completely eliminates nuclear off-target, and all operations are confined to the cytoplasm.
3. Risk: Clinical translation difficulty
   Solution: Therapeutic route uses mature technologies, in line with clinical standards; BCI route follows global development rhythm. The two routes are developed independently, and the therapeutic route can be translated quickly without being affected by frontier technologies.
